–1249":"1224–1249","1242":"1242","1340":"1340","1283":"1283","1290":"1290","1249":"1249","1259":"1259","1312":"1312","about 1239":"omkring 1239","1224":"1224","1245":"1245","1289":"1289","1222":"1222","1244":"1244","1342":"1342","of Beeston, Cheshire, England":"Beeston, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Beeston, Cheshire, England":"Beeston, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1245–1312":"1245–1312","1242–Male":"1242–Overleden","1244–Female":"1244–Overleden","1259–1340":"1259–1340","1290–1342":"1290–1342","1222–1283":"1222–1283","1224–1249":"1224–1249","1242":"1242","1340":"1340","1283":"1283","1290":"1290","1249":"1249","1259":"1259","1312":"1312","about 1239":"circa 1239","1224":"1224","1245":"1245","1289":"1289","1222":"1222","1244":"1244","1342":"1342","of Beeston, Cheshire, England":"Beeston, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Beeston, Cheshire, England":"Beeston, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1245–1312":"1245–1312","1242–Male":"1242–Deceased","1244–Female":"1244–Deceased","1259–1340":"1259–1340","1290–1342":"1290–1342","1222–1283":"1222–1283","1224–1249":"1224–1249","1242":"1242","1340":"1340","1283":"1283","1290":"1290","1249":"1249","1259":"1259","1312":"1312","about 1239":"about 1239","1224":"1224","1245":"1245","1289":"1289","1222":"1222","1244":"1244","1342":"1342","of Beeston, Cheshire, England":"Beeston, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Beeston, Cheshire, England":"Beeston, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Beeston","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","habitational name from any of the many places in England so called. Those in Nottinghamshire, Norfolk, and Yorkshire were settlements where bent grass grew (Old English <i>bēos</i> ‘rough grass’ + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’). In Bedfordshire it probably denoted a settlement on a bend (Old English <i>byge</i> + genitive singular <i>-es</i> + <i>tūn</i>). The hamlet stands on a marked bend of the river Yvel. In Cheshire it is named from a rock, below which trading took place (Old English <i>byge</i> ‘commerce’ + Old English <i>stān</i> ‘stone’). The reference is to a prominent crag where the remains of Beeston Castle stand. Compare   Beaston   and   Beeson  .","occasionally a topographic name for someone who lived in that part of a village known in Middle English as <i>bi este toun</i> ‘(place) at the east (end) of the village’."],"variants":[{"name":"Beston","meanings":["English: variant of   Beeston   and   Beaston  ."]},{"name":"Beeson","meanings":["English: variant of   Beeston  , a habitational name from a place called Beeston. The spelling reflects the local pronunciation of the Nottinghamshire placename, although this form is now quite widespread in England."]},{"name":"Beaston","meanings":["English: variant of   Beeston   (the more common form of the surname in England), a habitational name from any of various places called Beeston."]}]},{"name":"David","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the greatest of all the kings of Israel, whose history is recounted with great vividness in the first and second books of Samuel and elsewhere. As a boy he killed the giant Philistine Goliath with his slingshot. As king of Judah, and later of all Israel, he expanded the power of the Israelites and established the security of their kingdom. He was also noted as a poet, many of the Psalms being attributed to him. The Hebrew derivation of the name is uncertain; it is said by some to represent a nursery word meaning ‘darling’. It is a very popular Jewish name, but is almost equally common among Gentiles in the English-speaking world. It is particularly common in Wales and Scotland, having been borne by the patron saint of Wales (  see  Dewi   ) and by two medieval kings of Scotland."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lord David de Beeston was born in 1245, in Beeston, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Henry de Beeston, was 23 and his mother, Margery Beeston, was 22. He married Agnes de Bonbury in 1289, in Beeston, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1312, in Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 67."},"et":{"1245–1312":"1245–1312","1242–Male":"1242–Surnud","1244–Female":"1244–Surnud","1259–1340":"1259–1340","1290–1342":"1290–1342","1222–1283":"1222–1283","1224–1249":"1224–1249","1242":"1242","1340":"1340","1283":"1283","1290":"1290","1249":"1249","1259":"1259","1312":"1312","about 1239":"umbes 1239","1224":"1224","1245":"1245","1289":"1289","1222":"1222","1244":"1244","1342":"1342","of Beeston, Cheshire, England":"Beeston, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Beeston, Cheshire, England":"Beeston, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1245–1312":"1245–1312","1242–Male":"1242–Kuollut","1244–Female":"1244–Kuollut","1259–1340":"1259–1340","1290–1342":"1290–1342","1222–1283":"1222–1283","1224–1249":"1224–1249","1242":"1242","1340":"1340","1283":"1283","1290":"1290","1249":"1249","1259":"1259","1312":"1312","about 1239":"noin 1239","1224":"1224","1245":"1245","1289":"1289","1222":"1222","1244":"1244","1342":"1342","of Beeston, Cheshire, England":"Beeston, Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Beeston, Cheshire, England":"Beeston, Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1245–1312":"1245–1312","1242–Male":"1242–Décéd